This paper involves the use of generative adversarial networks (GANs) to generate sub-goals represented through motion templates, which can be used to train reinforcement learning agents. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), which deals with the development of algorithms and models for learning from data. 

The paper also involves the use of raw pixels and motion templates, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category cs.CV (Computer Vision), which deals with the analysis and interpretation of visual data. 

Additionally, the paper involves the use of reinforcement learning, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), which deals with the development of intelligent agents and systems. 

The paper also involves the use of agents in unknown environments, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category cs.RO (Robotics), which deals with the development of robots and autonomous systems. 

Finally, the paper involves the use of generative models, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category cs.GR (Graphics), which deals with the development of algorithms and models for generating visual content.
